    6	## What Was Tested
    7	Whether pi(x) can be expressed as a matrix power entry (A^x)_{ij} or trace Tr(A^x * B) for a fixed-size matrix A over Z. Also tested whether pi(x) mod m is a linear recurrence sequence (LRS) for small m.
    8	
    9	## Key Findings
    10	- Skolem-Mahler-Lech theorem: if pi(x) were LRS, then 1_prime(x) = pi(x) - pi(x-1) would also be LRS, but the prime indicator is not eventually periodic in its support -- contradiction
    11	- pi(x) mod m is NOT a linear recurrence mod m for any m tested (m = 2..20), with orders up to 20
    12	- Tr(A^x * B) and det(I - zA^x) extractors cannot yield pi(x) because they also produce LRS/quasi-LRS
    13	- The cumulative sum pi(x) inherits the non-LRS nature of the prime indicator
    14	
    15	## Verdict
    16	**CLOSED**
    17	**Failure Mode:** Information loss (pi(x) is provably not a linear recurrence sequence; no fixed-size matrix power encoding exists)
    18	
    19	## One-Line Summary
    20	pi(x) is not an LRS (proved via Skolem-Mahler-Lech + non-periodicity of primes); no fixed-size matrix power encoding.
